<!--
	Guided Lecture Notes worksheet: "Nonlinear Systems"
	Book sections (Exploring Differential Equations, geoff-cox/debookrs):
		c14-nlinsys/sec-nonlinear-systems.ptx  <- STUB (see TODO below)
	Old deck: source/notes/latex/ folder "09 systems-reduction-of-order"
	(thin; largely consumed by the c13 worksheet).
	Previous worksheet: ws-linear-systems.ptx; last worksheet of the GLN.

	TODO(geoff): the debookrs c14 chapter is currently a placeholder
	(sec-nonlinear-systems.ptx contains only a FUTURE-WORK stub), so
	unlike every other worksheet, this one could not track a book
	chapter. It is drafted ENTIRELY as proposed new material (standard
	course-capstone content: nonlinear systems, equilibria of systems,
	linearization near an equilibrium by dropping product terms,
	predator-prey interpretation, Euler's method on systems), fulfilling
	the arc promised in the c13 worksheet's conclusion. Every editorial
	choice here is up for review; once the debookrs c14 chapter is
	written, this worksheet should be revisited to track its notation
	and examples. Raised under the PR's Open questions.

	Per the sourcing rules, every worked instance here is fresh (checked
	against the whole book, the old decks, and earlier worksheets). Per
	the instructor overrides in CLAUDE.md section 4: no interactive
	content, and the whole topic stays on this one worksheet.

	Worksheet conventions: checklists/worksheet-conventions.md (see
	CLAUDE.md section 4 for this repo's parameters). In brief:
	  * Student/instructor split via component="stu" / component="key",
	    mirrored in structure; answers never live inside <fillin>.
	  * Worked problems: paired <exercise component="stu" workspace="Xin">
	    and <exercise component="key"> (statement + solution).
	  * True/False checks: one <exercise> + <solution component="key">.
	  * <page> = vertical print space, not topics; headings are
	    <p><term>...</term></p>; display math uses <md> (<me>/<men> are
	    prohibited here).
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-nonlinear-systems" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Nonlinear Systems</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li><p><term>Explain</term> why the exponential guess and superposition fail for nonlinear systems.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Find</term> equilibrium points of a system by solving <m>x' = 0</m> and <m>y' = 0</m> simultaneously.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Linearize</term> near an equilibrium by dropping product terms, and classify the neighborhood with linear-system tools.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Interpret</term> a predator&#8211;prey model's equations and cycles in words.</p></li>
			<li><p><term>Apply</term> Euler's method to a system when no formula exists.</p></li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 1 : Why nonlinear is different; equilibria of systems            -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>When the guess stops working.</term></p>

		<p>
			A term like <m>x\,y</m> breaks the linear machinery twice over: the
			exponential guess fails (substituting multiples of <m>e^{rt}</m>
			produces an <m>e^{2rt}</m> the other terms cannot cancel), and
			superposition fails with it&#8212;the sum of two solutions is no
			longer a solution. What survives is the <em>qualitative</em>
			program from c6, now in the phase plane: find where the system
			stands still, then study each neighborhood.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						An equilibrium point of a system is a point where
						<m>x'</m> and <m>y'</m> equal <fillin characters="4"/>
						<em>simultaneously</em>; a solution that starts at an equilibrium
						point <fillin characters="5"/> there forever.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						An equilibrium point of a system is a point where
						<m>x'</m> and <m>y'</m> equal <m>\underline{\textbf{zero}}</m>
						<em>simultaneously</em>; a solution that starts at an equilibrium
						point <m>\underline{\textbf{stays}}</m> there forever.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-tf-super">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>If <m>(x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>(x_2, y_2)</m> are solutions of a nonlinear system, then their sum is also a solution.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False. Superposition is a strictly linear privilege: a product
					term like <m>x\,y</m> evaluated at a sum produces cross-terms that
					the separate solutions never had to cancel. Losing superposition
					is precisely what makes nonlinear systems hard&#8212;and what
					pushes us back to qualitative and numerical tools.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-equilibria" component="stu" workspace="2.6in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the system
					<md>
						<mrow> \begin{cases} x' = x\,(2 - y) \\ y' = y\,(x - 3) \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					Find all equilibrium points. (Solve <m>x' = 0</m> and
					<m>y' = 0</m> together&#8212;watch for the case-by-case
					structure.)
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-equilibria" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Consider the system
					<md>
						<mrow> \begin{cases} x' = x\,(2 - y) \\ y' = y\,(x - 3) \end{cases} </mrow>
					</md>
					Find all equilibrium points. (Solve <m>x' = 0</m> and
					<m>y' = 0</m> together&#8212;watch for the case-by-case
					structure.)
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<m>x' = 0</m> requires <m>x = 0</m> or <m>y = 2</m>;
					<m>y' = 0</m> requires <m>y = 0</m> or <m>x = 3</m>. Intersecting
					the cases: <m>x = 0</m> pairs with <m>y = 0</m> (since
					<m>x = 0 \neq 3</m>), and <m>y = 2</m> pairs with <m>x = 3</m>.
					Two equilibria:
					<md>
						<mrow> (0, 0) \qquad\text{and}\qquad (3, 2). </mrow>
					</md>
					Mixing cases carelessly&#8212;say <m>x=0</m> with
					<m>x=3</m>&#8212;is the standard error; each equilibrium must
					satisfy one condition <em>from each equation</em>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 2 : Linearization near an equilibrium                            -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>Zooming in: linearization.</term></p>

		<p>
			Near an equilibrium, deviations are small&#8212;and a product of two
			small deviations is <em>tiny</em>. Writing the system in deviation
			variables and dropping those product terms leaves a linear system
			that governs the neighborhood, and c13's toolkit classifies it.
		</p>

		<!-- Reading check -->
		<p>
			<term>Reading check.</term> Fill in each blank from your reading.
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p component="stu">
						To linearize at an equilibrium, rewrite the system in deviation
						variables centered there and drop the <fillin characters="7"/> of
						deviations, which are negligibly small; the resulting
						<fillin characters="6"/> system describes trajectories near that
						equilibrium only.
					</p>
					<p component="key">
						To linearize at an equilibrium, rewrite the system in deviation
						variables centered there and drop the
						<m>\underline{\textbf{products}}</m> of deviations, which are
						negligibly small; the resulting <m>\underline{\textbf{linear}}</m>
						system describes trajectories near that equilibrium only.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-linearize" component="stu" workspace="3.4in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For the system on page 1:
					(a) Linearize at <m>(0,0)</m> by expanding and dropping product
					terms, and classify the equilibrium with c13's tools.
					(b) At <m>(3,2)</m>, substitute <m>x = 3 + u</m>,
					<m>y = 2 + w</m>, drop products of <m>u</m> and <m>w</m>, and
					describe the resulting linear system.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-linearize" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For the system on page 1:
					(a) Linearize at <m>(0,0)</m> by expanding and dropping product
					terms, and classify the equilibrium with c13's tools.
					(b) At <m>(3,2)</m>, substitute <m>x = 3 + u</m>,
					<m>y = 2 + w</m>, drop products of <m>u</m> and <m>w</m>, and
					describe the resulting linear system.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) Expanding: <m>x' = 2x - xy</m> and <m>y' = -3y + xy</m>. Near
					<m>(0,0)</m> the products are negligible:
					<md>
						<mrow> x' \approx 2x, \qquad y' \approx -3y. </mrow>
					</md>
					An uncoupled linear system with rates <m>2</m> and
					<m>-3</m>&#8212;one positive, one negative: a <em>saddle</em>. The
					origin attracts along the <m>y</m>-axis (prey extinct, predators
					starve) and repels along the <m>x</m>-axis (no predators, prey
					boom).
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) Substituting and using <m>2 - y = -w</m> and
					<m>x - 3 = u</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> u' = (3+u)(-w) = -3w - uw \amp \approx -3w, </mrow>
						<mrow> w' = (2+w)(u) = 2u + uw \amp \approx 2u. </mrow>
					</md>
					Each deviation drives the <em>other</em>: <m>u' = -3w</m>,
					<m>w' = 2u</m>&#8212;pure rotation with no growth or decay terms,
					so nearby trajectories orbit the equilibrium in closed loops
					rather than spiraling in or out.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-tf-global">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>A linearization describes the system's behavior across the entire phase plane.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False&#8212;it is a local magnifying glass, trustworthy only near
					the equilibrium where the dropped products really are tiny. Far
					away, the nonlinear terms take over. That is why each equilibrium
					gets its own linearization, and the global picture is stitched
					together from the neighborhoods.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 3 : Reading the model: predator-prey                             -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>What the model says: predators and prey.</term></p>

		<p>
			The page-1 system is a <term>predator&#8211;prey model</term>. The
			signs tell the story before any mathematics: ask which variable
			suffers from the other's presence, and which one needs the other to
			survive.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-interpret" component="stu" workspace="2.8in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>x' = x(2-y)</m>, <m>y' = y(x-3)</m>:
					(a) Which variable is the prey and which the predator? Cite the
					signs that decide it.
					(b) What does the equilibrium <m>(3,2)</m> mean ecologically?
					(c) Using the rotation found on page 2, narrate one full cycle
					starting from abundant prey and few predators.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-interpret" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					For <m>x' = x(2-y)</m>, <m>y' = y(x-3)</m>:
					(a) Which variable is the prey and which the predator? Cite the
					signs that decide it.
					(b) What does the equilibrium <m>(3,2)</m> mean ecologically?
					(c) Using the rotation found on page 2, narrate one full cycle
					starting from abundant prey and few predators.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					(a) <m>x</m> is the prey: its growth rate <m>2 - y</m> is
					<em>hurt</em> by <m>y</m>. <m>y</m> is the predator: its growth
					rate <m>x - 3</m> is <em>negative without enough</em>
					<m>x</m>&#8212;predators starve when prey are scarce.
				</p>
				<p>
					(b) At <m>(3,2)</m> the populations are perfectly balanced: three
					units of prey exactly sustain the predators, and two units of
					predators exactly cap the prey. Both populations hold constant.
				</p>
				<p>
					(c) Abundant prey let predators multiply; rising predators drive
					prey down; scarce prey starve the predators; falling predators
					release the prey to boom again&#8212;a closed loop around
					<m>(3,2)</m>, each population's peak trailing the other's. The
					boom-bust cycle is the model's signature, and real predator-prey
					data show exactly this lagged oscillation.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-tf-cycle">
			<title>True or False</title>
			<statement>
				<p>In the predator&#8211;prey cycle, the predator population peaks at the same time as the prey population.</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					False&#8212;the predator peak <em>lags</em> the prey peak.
					Predators are still multiplying while prey are already declining,
					because the feast that fueled them came earlier. The lag is
					visible in the phase plane as rotation: the two populations chase
					each other around the loop rather than rising and falling in
					unison.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ==================================================================== -->
	<!-- PAGE 4 : Numerics as the universal fallback; course capstone          -->
	<!-- ==================================================================== -->

	<page>
		<p><term>The universal fallback: Euler on a system.</term></p>

		<p>
			No formula solves the predator&#8211;prey system in elementary
			functions&#8212;but Euler's method never asked for a formula. It
			works on systems verbatim: evaluate <em>both</em> rates at the
			current point, and step <em>both</em> variables at once.
		</p>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-euler" component="stu" workspace="3.0in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Run two Euler steps with <m>h = 0.5</m> on
					<md>
						<mrow> x' = x\,(2-y), \qquad y' = y\,(x-3), \qquad (x_0, y_0) = (4, 1). </mrow>
					</md>
					Does the motion so far match the cycle narrative from page 3?
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>

		<exercise xml:id="ws-ns-ex-euler" component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Run two Euler steps with <m>h = 0.5</m> on
					<md>
						<mrow> x' = x\,(2-y), \qquad y' = y\,(x-3), \qquad (x_0, y_0) = (4, 1). </mrow>
					</md>
					Does the motion so far match the cycle narrative from page 3?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					<term>Step 1.</term> At <m>(4,1)</m>:
					<m>x' = 4(2-1) = 4</m> and <m>y' = 1(4-3) = 1</m>, so
					<md>
						<mrow> (x_1, y_1) = (4 + 0.5\cdot 4,\ 1 + 0.5\cdot 1) = (6,\ 1.5). </mrow>
					</md>
					<term>Step 2.</term> At <m>(6, 1.5)</m>:
					<m>x' = 6(0.5) = 3</m> and <m>y' = 1.5(3) = 4.5</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow> (x_2, y_2) = (6 + 1.5,\ 1.5 + 2.25) = (7.5,\ 3.75). </mrow>
					</md>
				</p>
				<p>
					Both populations are climbing, with the predators accelerating as
					prey pile up&#8212;the opening phase of the cycle exactly as
					narrated: feast first, reckoning later. (A computer taking
					thousands of tiny steps would carry the loop all the way around.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<title>Looking back</title>
			<p>
				This worksheet closes the course's loop. One equation or many,
				linear or not, polite forcing or switched&#8212;the toolkit is the
				same three lenses: <em>exact formulas</em> where structure allows
				(separation, integrating factors, characteristic roots, Laplace),
				<em>qualitative analysis</em> where it doesn't (equilibria, phase
				lines and planes, stability), and <em>numerics</em> everywhere
				(Euler's method and its refinements). Knowing which lens to reach
				for&#8212;that judgment is the real content of MA 311.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>
</worksheet>
